year=3F =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in practice this is very small, because we do th=
is trade on an exchange with a clearinghouse that requires us to post daily=
 margin, so there should always be enough money for you to pay me for my bo=
nd.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trade here is roughly =E2=80=
=9CI bought a Treasury bond for $1 million and sold it for $1 million,=E2=
=80=9D so how much money should I have to put up to do the trade=3F The low=
er and upper bounds are:</p> <ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-le=
ft: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">$1 million mi=
nus $1 million is $0: I have bought for $1 million and sold for $1 million =
so my net position is zero.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">$1 milli=
on plus=C2=A0$1 million is $2 million: I have bought for $1 million and sol=
d for $1 million so my gross position is $2 million.</li> </ul> <p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">In practice the answer is between those bounds, but much =
much closer to zero than to $2 million. Buying a thing and selling almost t=
he same thing is=C2=A0<em>mostly=C2=A0</em>equivalent to not buying it in t=
he first place, so I don=E2=80=99t have to pay very much to do it.</p> <p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why would I do this trade=3F (It is called =E2=80=
